#: src/project_layout.md:1
msgid "Project Layout"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:3
msgid ""
"Maturin expects a particular project layout depending on the contents of the "
"package."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:6
msgid "Pure Rust project"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:8
msgid ""
"For a pure Rust project, the structure is as expected and what you get from "
"`cargo new`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:19
msgid ""
"Maturin will add a necessary `__init__.py` to the package when building the "
"wheel. For convenience, this file includes the following:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:26
msgid "\"__all__\""
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:30
msgid "such that the module functions may be called directly with:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:37
msgid "rather than:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:43
msgid ""
"**Note**: there is currently no way to tell maturin to include extra data (e."
"g. `package_data` in setuptools) for a pure Rust project. Instead, consider "
"using the layout described below for the mixed Rust/Python project."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:47
msgid "Mixed Rust/Python project"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:49
msgid ""
"To create a mixed Rust/Python project, add a directory with your package "
"name (i.e. matching `lib.name` in your `Cargo.toml`) to contain the Python "
"source:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:64
msgid ""
"Note that in a mixed Rust/Python project, maturin _does not_ modify the "
"existing `__init__.py` in the root package, so now to import the rust module "
"in Python you must use:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:72
msgid ""
"You can modify `__init__.py` yourself (see above) if you would like to "
"import Rust functions from a higher-level namespace."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:75
msgid ""
"You can specify a different python source directory in `pyproject.toml` by "
"setting `tool.maturin.python-source`, for example"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:77
msgid "**pyproject.toml**"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:79
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"python-source = \"python\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:84
msgid "then the project structure would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:99
msgid "**Note**"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:101
msgid ""
"This structure is recommended to avoid [a common `ImportError` pitfall]"
"(https://github.com/PyO3/maturin/issues/490)"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:104
msgid "Alternate Python source directory (src layout)"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:106
msgid ""
"Having a directory with `package_name` in the root of the project can "
"occasionally cause confusion as Python allows importing local packages and "
"modules. A popular way to avoid this is with the `src`\\-layout, where the "
"Python package is nested within a `src` directory. Unfortunately this "
"interferes with the structure of a typical Rust project. Fortunately, Python "
"is not particular about the name of the parent source directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:113
msgid "maturin will detect the following src layout automatically:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:128
msgid "Import Rust as a submodule of your project"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:130
msgid ""
"If the Python module created by Rust has the same name as the Python package "
"in a mixed Rust/Python project, IDEs might get confused. You might also want "
"to discourage end users from using the Rust functions directly by giving it "
"a different name, say '\\_my_project'. This can be done by adding `module-"
"name = <package name>.<rust pymodule name>` to the `[tool.maturin]` in your "
"`pyproject.toml`. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:134
msgid ""
"```toml\n"
"[tool.maturin]\n"
"module-name = \"my_project._my_project\"\n"
"```"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:139
msgid "Update the module name in `lib.rs` to match the expected module name:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:147
msgid ""
"If you are using the `pyo3` bindings, you can alternatively add `#[pyo3(name "
"= ...)]` to the `#[pymodule]` declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:155
msgid ""
"You can then import your Rust module inside your Python source as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:161
msgid ""
"IDEs can then recognize the `_my_project` module as separate from your main "
"Python source module. This allows for code completion of the types inside "
"your Rust Python module for certain IDEs."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:164
msgid "Adding Python type information"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:166
msgid "To distribute typing information, you need to add:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:168
msgid ""
"an empty marker file called `py.typed` in the root of the Python package"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:169
msgid "inline types in Python files and/or `.pyi` \"stub\" files"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:171
msgid ""
"In a pure Rust project, add type stubs in a `<module_name>.pyi` file in the "
"project root. Maturin will automatically include this file along with the "
"required `py.typed` file for you."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:184
msgid ""
"In a mixed Rust/Python project, additional files in the Python source dir "
"(but not in `.gitignore`) will be automatically included in the build "
"outputs (source distribution and/or wheel). Type information can be "
"therefore added to the root Python package directory as you might do in a "
"pure Python package. This requires you to add the `py.typed` marker file "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:206
msgid "Data"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:208
msgid ""
"You can add wheel data by creating a `<module_name>.data` folder or setting "
"its location as `data` in pyproject.toml under `[tool.maturin]` or in Cargo."
"toml under `[project.metadata.maturin]`."
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:210
msgid "The data folder may have the following subfolder:"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:212
msgid ""
"`data`: The contents of this folder will simply be unpacked into the "
"virtualenv"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:213
msgid ""
"`scripts`: Treated similar to entry points, files in there are installed as "
"standalone executable"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:214
msgid "`headers`: For `.h` C header files"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:215
msgid "`purelib`: This also exists, but seems to be barely used"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:216
msgid "`platlib`: This also exists, but seems to be barely used"
msgstr ""

#: src/project_layout.md:218
msgid ""
"If you add a symlink in the data directory, we'll include the actual file so "
"you have more flexibility."
msgstr ""
